        "comment": {
            "name": "comment",
            "type": "com.atlassian.jira.issue.fields.CommentSystemField",
            "value": [
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/18016",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=fab",
                        "name": "fab",
                        "displayName": "Fabien MARTY",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Zend_Cache doesn't send Content-Type header.\n\nSomething like this should work, no ?\n\n{noformat} \n\nrequire 'Zend\/Cache.php')\n[...] we make $cache object\n\nheader(\"Content-Type...\");\n\n$cache->start()\n\nrequire_once 'Model.php'\n[...]\n\n[...] your work to make the XML file\necho($xmlString);\n\n{noformat} ",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=fab",
                        "name": "fab",
                        "displayName": "Fabien MARTY",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-12-19T13:46:25.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-12-19T13:46:25.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/18017",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=skina",
                        "name": "skina",
                        "displayName": "Daniel Skinner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "It's a possible solution but that wouldn't work in my case or most common cases when using Zend_Controller.\n\nIn my case the module\/controller\/action route will determine the Content-Type header which will be set on the Response object. Since Zend_Cache is setup in the bootstrap, it does not go through the entire route sequence to determine what the Content-Type should be.\n\nAs it stands your solution would work for a lot of cases when using Zend_Cache\/Zend_Cache_Frontend_Page in a simple application. However, when using Zend_Cache\/Zend_Cache_Frontend_Page with Zend_Controller you are essentially limited to produce text\/html responses.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=skina",
                        "name": "skina",
                        "displayName": "Daniel Skinner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-12-19T14:08:46.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-12-19T14:08:46.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/18724",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=fab",
                        "name": "fab",
                        "displayName": "Fabien MARTY",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "I just commited a change for this into the SVN trunk\n\nplease try it (you will have to set the backend option content_type_memorization = true) and reopen this task if problem\n\nregards",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=fab",
                        "name": "fab",
                        "displayName": "Fabien MARTY",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2008-01-30T17:24:41.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2008-01-30T17:24:41.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/18736",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=skina",
                        "name": "skina",
                        "displayName": "Daniel Skinner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "The new Zend_Cache_Frontend_Page class definately works in my case. The Content-Type header is correctly remembered and sent along with the cached output.\n\nThe content_type_memorization is a frontend option, not a backend one.\n\nThanks for this fix!",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=skina",
                        "name": "skina",
                        "displayName": "Daniel Skinner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2008-01-31T05:23:09.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2008-01-31T05:23:09.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/21718",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=gspeicher",
                        "name": "gspeicher",
                        "displayName": "Geoff Speicher",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Problem is not limited to Content-type header; other important headers (Expires, for example) are also lost.  Is there any good reason not to remember and re-use *all* response headers for cached pages?  The patch is even simpler than the patch to add content_type_memorization.  Just save the entire headers_list() array in the cache and spit them all back.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=gspeicher",
                        "name": "gspeicher",
                        "displayName": "Geoff Speicher",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2008-05-12T11:48:24.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2008-05-12T11:48:24.000+0000"
                },
                {
